> protective which is also awesome. I had an exhaust vent installed in my
> shop for my laser cutter and had an extra duct installed so that I can ge=
t
> up a spray paint booth later. Too cold for that shit now! I have a
> hydroponics tent out there now with a small heater in it to keep the lase=
r
> tube from freezing this winter. The tent accepts ducting so it'll be easy
> to get the laser hooked up the rest of the way and running.
>
> Bought a UTV (A Polaris Ranger XP 1000 Northstar Ultimate) (mouthful) and
> a plow attachment, so I can keep our 1/4 mile long driveway plowed this
> winter. That will be interesting. Eli gets in with me and rides in the
> passenger seat looking out the windshield just like a person. It's funny.
> It's a half-mile to the mailbox so I usually drive the UTV down there.
>
> So, about Jeremy. He's making incremental changes to a design that I thin=
k
> needs an overhaul. I still feel strongly that we need to do these things:
>
> -Redesign for more conventional materials. I want to design a housing tha=
t
> can be built with low-cost softwood lumber in sizes that can be purchased
> at Home Depot and Lowe's, and can be cut to size by staff right there in
> the store so that the builder leaves with materials that are already
> cut-to-size. User will still have to drill holes but otherwise I'd like t=
o
> not require them to own some kind of power saw.
>
> -Relegate Acrylic parts to machinery only. Acrylic machine guts installed
> inside a wooden box.
>
> -Redesign the lid-perch system to eliminate water incursion.
>
> -Strongly consider eliminating the servo and replacing it with a simple D=
C
> motor. I'm very concerned about the failure rate on the low-cost servos w=
e
> rely on, and I don't think the answer is asking people to buy a $25-$30
> servo instead of a $6 one, when we could just design for a $5 DC gearmoto=
r.
>
> -Reduce the parts/tools count. There are some oddball items that users
> have to buy (silicone chef rubber bands, metal hitch pins) that increase
> the cost and procurement times for parts. Where possible, I'd like to
> eliminate these or replace them with items that can be bought at Home
> Depot, Lowes, or (gag) Wal-Mart. Most of the US population has easy acces=
s
> to one or all of these outlets.
>
> So it's a little weird to have someone making incremental changes without
> our history of knowledge about the compromises we had to make, and the
> existing known flaws in the physical build. It's not a good sign that he
> didn't open a dialog about potential changes before deciding what he
> thought should change. That's a bit hostile, even if not malicious in
> intent.
>
> If he does unleash his own version of the Crowbox, we will incur any
> support issues rising out of his design changes. How will users know whic=
h
> Crowbox they're building? Our build videos aren't going to be valid for h=
is
> modified parts, and if someone starts out building a Crowbox from our
> instructional videos but using his parts, they may end up chemically
> welding their parts into useless subassemblies. So what level and quality
> of instruction and support is he prepared to offer for users who want to
> build his version?
>
> I'm very concerned about how we'd tag and identify his modified Crowbox,
> for the sake of users who are trying to find build instructions, operatin=
g
> instructions, or technical support.
>
> I don't have any problem with Jeremy branching the Github repository but
> it's not super clear to me what he'd be changing in the software. I assum=
ed
> that any modifications to the software would involve the addition of
> cameras or other types of sensors, or wifi communication. We would need t=
o
> review his code submissions to make sure he doesn't adversely affect the
> performance or stability of the software.
>
> Over my career I had the opportunity to work with and learn from very
> capable professionals who possessed the exceedingly rare ability to be
> utterly objective about their own work and its viability. This is less
> common among hobbyists and hackers, where building or programming somethi=
ng
> to your own satisfaction is NOT the same as building something that will
> then be turned over to the public for use. I don't know where on the
> Hobbyist<->Objective Professional spectrum this guy falls but to begin
> with, I'll assume way towards Hobbyist. This is a space in which I don't
> give anyone benefit of the doubt- I have to be convinced otherwise. But
> we'd learn a lot about him by looking over his parts and his changes to t=
he
> software.
>
> By the way, Jeremy has a point when it comes to the water-thin #3 formula
> of Sci-Grip solvent. In fact, I use the water thin formula for all of my
> personal projects and most of the Crowbox prototyping. Application is mor=
e
> precise and this formula chemically welds the parts together much more
> quickly. However, this stuff evaporates incredibly quickly- you can watch=
 a
> large puddle of it disappear in front of you- it takes seconds. Or you ca=
n
> watch your entire $30 can of it evaporate in minutes if you forget to cap
> it. Also, it must be applied with a syringe and precision applicator tip =
or
> a special plastic squeeze bottle with precision applicator tip. So there
> are some materials-handling concerns with this formula as well as special
> equipment required. The other thing he doesn't know about our experience
> with the Crowbox is that our recommended syrup-consistency #16 Sci-Grip
> solvent is that it is partially thickened with dissolved plastic. This
> means that the thicker formula adds body in addition to welding parts
> together- it deposits liquid plastic into the joints, which cures to
> plastic. This is very helpful in making sure that [less experienced
> builders] get the benefit of the gap-filling feature of the thicker solve=
nt
> formula. This helps make sure they don't end up with dry/partial joints o=
r
> gaps in parts that really need a seal. The #16 formula is far more
> forgiving and the #3 formula requires some skill to properly apply and
> inspection of the finished joints to ensure the weld is complete.
>
> On a Crowbox which features a wood housing, I probably wouldn't have a
> problem asking users to use the more complicated #3 solvent on the intern=
al
> machine parts. It'd be cleaner and, inside the machine, less critical to
> ensure joints are absolutely complete.
>
> I have no argument against a modular design which can be field-stripped
> for cleaning, repair, or possibly even upgrading. It's something we did n=
ot
> design into this version of the Crowbox but the benefits are obvious.
>
> Again, no trouble letting him branch the GitHub repository. It's public
> anyway so we are not set up to stop that, by design. But I really want to
> figure out how we avoid confusing users or running into trouble with his
> version-and-a-half released on the group.
>
> At a high level, I'm feeling more like we need to pursue success on our
> own again. I want to build and operate a Crowbox that functions all the w=
ay
> to Phase Four, including the compliment of participating Crows. I see cro=
ws
> every couple of days here but they just fly overhead. I bet I could start
> convincing them to land. We're out in the country on 10 acres, with 5 acr=
es
> of hay and tall Fescue, so we have lots of wild rodents. I need to figure
> out a strategy (likely just an elevated platform) where I could provide
> peanuts to the crows without feeding the field mice, too. I also need to
> make sure I can set up my site in a way that our various neighbors' roami=
ng
> barn cats can't assault the crows. See, guys who are building contraption=
s
> out of ugly discarded fence wood or store-bought plastic Rubbermaid
> containers are making good progress while we branched to design something
> than anyone could build and operate. It feels a bit like the community
> wants to see the success on YouTube more than they want to participate in
> achieving the success so we may want to seriously consider a parallel
> project where we design and build whatever we need to continue our own
> research, while continuing to support the community and their
> easier-to-build-and-maintain current version of the Crowbox.
>
> My attention is pretty divided right now, so apologies. This is a very ra=
w
> data dump on you and I think I wandered a bit. It'd be good to make anoth=
er
> attempt to sync up via webchat so that I don't have this huge backlog of
> thoughts and information that I keep trying to express every time we're
> discussing some other aspect of the project.
